Ntu-exam
[試題] 98下 齊東耿 歐洲文學1800以後 期中考











標題[試題] 98下 齊東耿 歐洲文學1800以後 期中考

作者

travellerjay

                (travellerjay)
            
            


看板

NTU-Exam



時間

                    2010-04-09 15:01:06
            








課程名稱︰歐洲文學1800以後
課程性質︰外文系選修
課程教師︰齊東耿
開課學院：文學院
開課系所︰外文系
考試日期（年月日）︰99.03.26
考試時限（分鐘）：170分鐘
是否需發放獎勵金：是
（如未明確表示，則不予發放）

試題 :

This is a short exam, 65 points. You are not allowed to use your book or your
notes. Pay attention to the relative importance of given questions.

I. Goethe Short Answer[10]:






What is the "Dies irae"?

What is Walpurgisnacht?

When was Faust part 1 published?

When did the real Johannes Faust supposedly live?

Who is Lieschen?

II. Medium Answer[40]

According to Immanuel Kant, "What is Enlightment?"(This is NOT a question about
complicated Kantian philosophy!)[5]

What is God's bet with Mephisto?[3]

What is Mephisto's initial wager to Faust?[3]

What is Faust's wager to Mephisto? Please explain. What is the real meaning of
the bet? What does it suggest about Faust's nature, about Human Nature?[6]

Why does Faust turn to magic and evil at the beginning of the play?[5]

What is so important about the scene of translation of the first sentence of
the Greek Gospel of John?("In the beginning was...")[5]

Describe the character of Margarete[Gretchen/Gretel]. Why does she accept Faust
and go along with him until the end?[5]

What is so significent and symbolic about the Encyclopedie, ou dictionnaire
raisonne des sciences, des arts et des metiers (Encyclopedia, or a systematic
dictionary of the sciences, arts and crafts), 1751-1772 by Diderot, d'Alembert,
et al.[3]

What does Faust respond when Margarete asks him whether he believes in God?[5]

Short Essay[15]
Describe the scene of Faust's rapture in the Cavern in the Forest. This occurs
at the height of his love for Margarete, before it begins to have bad
consequences. Faust addresses the "Sublime Spirit" but is later interrupted by
that more profane spirit, Mephistopheles. Why is Faust alone in his joy? What
is do significant about this scene that it could be called the Romantic
center-piece of the whole play? Please explain.



End

